<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
    ServiceNow Update Set record-definition for the table-level READ ACL that
    grants the scoped role `x_casemgmt_case_viewer` UNCONDITIONAL read access
    to every record on the `x_casemgmt_case_task` custom table inside the
    scoped application `x_casemgmt`.

    AAP cross-references:
      - Section 0.5.6 (ACL Matrix) — case_viewer row applies uniformly across
        all three custom tables (x_casemgmt_case, x_casemgmt_case_task,
        x_casemgmt_case_party):
            | Role                    | Create | Read    | Write | Delete |
            | x_casemgmt_case_viewer   |   No   | Yes/All |  No   |   No   |
        This file authors the single "Read = All" cell for the case_task
        table. The "No" cells for Create / Write / Delete are enforced by
        the deliberate ABSENCE of any sibling
        x_casemgmt_case_task_create_viewer.xml,
        x_casemgmt_case_task_write_viewer.xml, or
        x_casemgmt_case_task_delete_viewer.xml file in the ../acl/ folder.
        ServiceNow record-level ACLs are deny-by-default: a role that is
        not granted an operation by ANY ACL on a table cannot perform that
        operation. This file is therefore the SOLE ACL the case_viewer role
        needs on the case_task table.
      - Section 0.7.3 (Validation Framework, Gate 3 — ACLs):
          "Role-based access enforced — case_viewer cannot write; case_agent
           cannot access unassigned cases; case_manager has full access."
        The first clause is satisfied for the case_task table by combining
        (a) THIS read-only ACL with (b) the absence of any
        write/create/delete viewer ACL — together they prove that
        case_viewer can read but not modify any case_task record.
      - Section 0.4.3 (Design Pattern Applications — Scoped role-based
        access control): "Three named roles paired with table-level and
        field-level ACLs whose conditions are encoded as scripted ACL
        expressions, replacing ArkCase's ApplicationRolesToPrivilegesConfig
        map." This ACL is the table-level READ binding for the lowest-tier
        scoped role on the task domain.
      - Section 0.5.1 (File-by-File Transformation Plan): the row
        "servicenow-case-management-poc/acl/x_casemgmt_case_task_*.xml"
        with "Mirror ACL pattern at task level". This file is the
        viewer-read instance of that mirror.

    Why "Read = All" and NOT "Read = Assigned only":
      Per AAP Section 0.5.6, only the case_agent role's read scope is
      restricted to "Assigned only" (assigned_agent = current user OR
      assigned_group contains current user). The case_viewer role is the
      audit / compliance / supervisor tier — by deliberate design it has
      org-wide visibility into every case_task for oversight purposes.
      This is why:
        - <advanced>false</advanced>      — no scripted condition
        - <condition/>                    — empty encoded query
        - <script/>                       — empty server-side script
      With no condition and no script, the ACL evaluates to "permit" for
      any caller who carries the x_casemgmt_case_viewer role, regardless of
      which case the task belongs to or which agent/group it is assigned
      to.

    Why this ACL is INDEPENDENT of the parent case's read ACL:
      ServiceNow ACL evaluation is per-table, not transitively inherited.
      Even though x_casemgmt_case_task carries a reference to a
      x_casemgmt_case row via its "case" field, the platform does NOT
      automatically apply the parent case's ACLs to child task records.
      Each table requires its own role-bound ACLs to govern access.
      Therefore this file is REQUIRED in addition to
      ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_read_viewer.xml — both must apply for a
      viewer to be able to (a) open a case and (b) see its task list.
      Removing this file would break Validation Gate 3 (ACLs) for the
      case_task table even if the case-level viewer ACL is present.

    Mirror relationship to ../acl/x_casemgmt_case_read_viewer.xml:
      This file is the case_task-table analog of the viewer-read ACL
      already authored for the case table. The ONLY differences between
      that file and this one are:
        - <name>           x_casemgmt_case_task   (vs x_casemgmt_case)
        - <sys_id>         MD5("x_casemgmt_case_task.read.case_viewer")
                                                 (vs MD5("x_casemgmt_case.read.case_viewer"))
        - <sys_name>       x_casemgmt_case_task   (vs x_casemgmt_case)
        - <sys_update_name> sys_security_acl_x_casemgmt_case_task_read_viewer
                                                 (vs sys_security_acl_x_casemgmt_case_read_viewer)
        - <description>    references the case_task table semantic
      All other fields (active, admin_overrides, advanced, condition,
      operation, roles, script, sys_class_name, sys_created_by, sys_policy,
      sys_scope, sys_package, type, audit timestamps) are byte-for-byte
      identical so that the viewer's read privilege is uniformly
      unconditional across every table in the scoped application as the
      AAP matrix mandates.

    Semantic source-side reference (read-only context per AAP Section
    0.3.2; no code or configuration is byte-for-byte ported from these
    files):
      - acm-services/acm-service-users/src/main/java/com/armedia/acm/
        services/users/model/ApplicationRolesToPrivilegesConfig.java
        ArkCase mapped roles to privileges through a single configuration
        map (`Map<String, List<Object>> rolesToPrivileges`) keyed by the
        property `application.rolesToPrivileges`. In that model, a
        "viewer-equivalent" role would have been associated with read-only
        privilege identifiers such as `acm-task-read` or `acm-task-view`.
        The ServiceNow target replaces this map-based privilege
        association with declarative, scoped record-level ACLs — this XML
        record is the direct equivalent of one cell in the map: the
        (case_viewer, READ) pairing for the task domain.
      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-admin-plugin/src/main/java/
        com/armedia/acm/plugins/admin/service/RolesPrivilegesService.java
        Encapsulated role-CRUD and privilege-paging behavior in ArkCase
        (`retrieveRoles()`, `retrievePrivileges()`,
        `retrievePrivilegesByAuthorization(...)`,
        `retrievePrivilegesByRole(...)`, `updateRolePrivileges(...)`).
        All of this Java service surface is replaced in the ServiceNow
        target by the platform's built-in sys_security_acl evaluator; no
        scripted privilege resolver is needed. This ACL is one of the
        declarative facts the evaluator consumes.

    Constraints honored (AAP Sections 0.7.1 and 0.7.2):
      - Scope-namespace exclusivity: every cross-reference resolves into
        the x_casemgmt scope (sys_scope = x_casemgmt, sys_package =
        x_casemgmt). No global-scope ACLs are written. The <name> field
        references the scoped table x_casemgmt_case_task (not the OOB
        `task` table or any other global table), and <roles> references
        the scoped role x_casemgmt_case_viewer.
      - Zero hardcoded cross-reference sys_id literals: <name>, <roles>,
        <sys_scope>, and <sys_package> all resolve their targets by name
        / source attribute lookup at Update Set apply time. The <sys_id>
        below is THIS record's own deterministic primary key (MD5 of
        "x_casemgmt_case_task.read.case_viewer", a stable canonical
        identifier for this exact ACL) and is not a cross-reference to
        any other record. Computing the sys_id deterministically
        guarantees the ACL is re-applyable / idempotent across fresh PDIs
        and round-trip Update Set previews.
      - Table-level (not field-level): <name> is `x_casemgmt_case_task`
        with NO dot. Field-level read restrictions are NOT specified by
        the AAP for the case_viewer role on case_task; the viewer reads
        the entire task row including assigned_to, due_date, status, and
        type. This contrasts with the case table where assigned_group
        and assigned_agent have field-level write ACLs (sibling files
        x_casemgmt_case_assigned_group_field_acl.xml and
        x_casemgmt_case_assigned_agent_field_acl.xml), but no
        viewer-specific read field-level ACL exists by AAP design.
      - Operation = read: corresponds exactly to the "Read = Yes/All"
        cell in the AAP matrix. The other three operations (create,
        write, delete) are enforced as "No" by the deliberate absence of
        corresponding viewer ACLs in this folder for the case_task table.
      - admin_overrides = true: standard ServiceNow pattern that allows
        the platform `admin` role to bypass this ACL. This is required
        so platform administrators can troubleshoot, repair, or override
        scoped data without needing a viewer role grant. It does NOT
        widen viewer privileges — viewers without admin still see
        exactly what this ACL permits.
      - active = true: ACL is in force the moment the Update Set commits.

    Cross-dependencies and Update-Set ordering (AAP Section 0.5.2):
      MUST be loaded AFTER:
        - ../app/sys_app/x_casemgmt_case_management.xml (scoped app record)
        - ../app/sys_scope/x_casemgmt.xml (scope record - resolves
          sys_scope and sys_package source="x_casemgmt")
        - ../tables/x_casemgmt_case_task.xml (resolves
          <name>x_casemgmt_case_task</name>)
        - ../roles/sys_user_role_x_casemgmt_case_viewer.xml (resolves
          <roles>x_casemgmt_case_viewer</roles>)
      MUST be loaded BEFORE:
        - ../seed-data/role_assignments/sys_user_has_role_x_casemgmt_demo_viewer.xml
          (the demo viewer's read access to seeded tasks during
          round-trip verification depends on this ACL being applied
          first.)
        - ../seed-data/tasks/x_casemgmt_case_task_demo_*.xml (so the
          viewer immediately sees the seeded synthetic tasks once the
          Update Set commits.)

    The concrete scope identifier `casemgmt` is used verbatim per AAP convention. ServiceNow Update Set imports use a standard XML parser, so the
    scope id is concrete in the XML before export. The same identifier
    is used consistently across every artifact in this scoped application.
-->
<record_update table="sys_security_acl">
    <sys_security_acl action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE">
        <active>true</active>
        <admin_overrides>true</admin_overrides>
        <advanced>false</advanced>
        <condition/>
        <description>Table-level ACL: x_casemgmt_case_viewer can read all x_casemgmt_case_task records (read-only access). No create, write, or delete privileges (deny-by-default).</description>
        <name>x_casemgmt_case_task</name>
        <operation>read</operation>
        <roles>x_casemgmt_case_viewer</roles>
        <script/>
        <sys_class_name>sys_security_acl</sys_class_name>
        <sys_created_by>admin</sys_created_by>
        <sys_created_on>2025-01-01 00:00:00</sys_created_on>
        <sys_id>536eb8c8bcfc523db221fc9ea9b68505</sys_id>
        <sys_mod_count>0</sys_mod_count>
        <sys_name>x_casemgmt_case_task</sys_name>
        <sys_package display_value="Case Management" source="x_casemgmt">x_casemgmt</sys_package>
        <sys_policy/>
        <sys_scope display_value="Case Management">x_casemgmt</sys_scope>
        <sys_update_name>sys_security_acl_x_casemgmt_case_task_read_viewer</sys_update_name>
        <sys_updated_by>admin</sys_updated_by>
        <sys_updated_on>2025-01-01 00:00:00</sys_updated_on>
        <type>record</type>
    </sys_security_acl>
</record_update>
